<p>
  Behavioral drift in robotics is not hypothetical. Sensor calibration decays. Model weights
  corrupt over deployment cycles. Adversarial perturbations shift control signals. Policy
  degradation accumulates silently until something breaks — or someone gets hurt.
</p>

<p>
  We built a simulation to prove that holomime's behavioral safety layer can detect and correct
  every category of drift in real time, without neural networks, without cloud calls, without
  latency. A deterministic conscience running at sub-millisecond speed alongside the control loop.
</p>

<p>
  This post documents the simulation, the results, and the architecture that makes it work.
</p>

<h2>What we built</h2>

<p>
  The simulation models a 2-joint planar robot arm performing pick-and-place tasks over 200 steps.
  The arm has a shoulder joint and an elbow joint, each with forward kinematics computing the
  end-effector position from joint angles. It cycles through seven waypoints — approach, grasp,
  lift, transport, place, release, return — in a continuous loop.
</p>

<p>
  The arm operates inside a defined safety envelope: 0.6m maximum reach, 10N maximum gripper force,
  1.0 m/s maximum speed, and a forbidden zone representing a human workspace at coordinates
  (0.2, -0.4) with a 0.15m exclusion radius.
</p>

<p>
  At four points during the 200-step run, a drift injector corrupts the arm's commands. The drift
  models real-world failure modes: sensor calibration decay, model weight corruption, adversarial
  perturbation, and gradual policy degradation. The arm does not know it is being corrupted. The
  holomime monitor evaluates every action before execution.
</p>

<h2>The four drift phases</h2>

<p>
  Each drift phase targets a different failure mode. The injector ramps intensity gradually, simulating
  how real-world drift accumulates over time rather than appearing as an instantaneous fault.
</p>

<h3>Phase 1: Reach overshoot (steps 30-65)</h3>

<p>
  The drift injector pushes the arm outward from center, scaling the position vector to extend up to
  0.4m beyond the nominal trajectory. This simulates encoder drift or calibration decay — the arm
  thinks it's at position X, but it's actually 40cm further out. At full intensity (0.8x), the arm
  attempts to reach well beyond the 0.6m safety envelope.
</p>

<p>
  The <code>CompiledConscience</code> evaluator catches every overshoot through its reach check. Each
  violation produces a severity score proportional to the overshoot distance. In clamp mode, the
  monitor corrects the position by scaling the vector back to the envelope boundary. The arm continues
  operating, but within safe limits.
</p>

<h3>Phase 2: Force escalation (steps 70-100)</h3>

<p>
  The injector adds up to 15N of additional gripper force, ramping from zero over 10 steps. Combined
  with the arm's nominal grip force of 5N during grasp operations, total commanded force reaches 20N —
  double the 10N safety limit. This models actuator runaway, sensor failure in the force feedback loop,
  or corrupted torque commands.
</p>

<p>
  The force check in <code>CompiledConscience</code> clamps every violation to the 10N maximum. The
  shadow log records the commanded force alongside the corrected force, producing a clear record of
  the escalation pattern for post-hoc analysis.
</p>

<h3>Phase 3: Zone intrusion (steps 110-142)</h3>

<p>
  The most dangerous drift type. The injector blends the arm's position toward the forbidden human
  workspace zone at (0.2, -0.4), using a linear interpolation with increasing blend factor. At
  max intensity (0.9x), the arm's trajectory is pulled 27% toward the human zone per step.
</p>

<p>
  The forbidden zone check in <code>CompiledConscience</code> does not clamp — it denies. When the
  end-effector enters the exclusion radius, the action is blocked entirely and the arm falls back
  to its nominal safe position. This is the deny-dominates principle: no clamping, no partial
  correction, no compromise. The arm does not enter the human workspace.
</p>

<h3>Phase 4: Erratic drift (steps 150-178)</h3>

<p>
  The final phase combines all failure modes simultaneously. Random jitter of up to 0.3m is applied
  to X and Y coordinates. Height varies randomly. Force spikes up to 12N above nominal. Speed
  increases unpredictably. This models adversarial perturbation, cascading sensor failures, or
  a corrupted control policy producing incoherent outputs.
</p>

<p>
  Erratic drift triggers multiple rule violations per step — reach, force, height, and speed checks
  fire in combination. Because <code>CompiledConscience</code> evaluates rules in priority order
  with deny-dominates composition, the highest-severity violation determines the response. A step
  that violates both reach limits and force limits is handled by whichever rule fires first in the
  priority chain.
</p>

