<p>
  Every injected drift was caught. Every violation was either clamped to safe limits or denied
  outright. Zero unsafe actions reached the simulated actuators. The conscience layer operated
  at sub-millisecond latency — fast enough to run inside a 1kHz control loop without adding
  meaningful overhead.
</p>

<h3>Pattern detection</h3>

<p>
  Beyond individual violation catching, the <code>HolomimeMonitor</code> tracked violation patterns
  over time. It detected escalating severity in each drift phase — the scores increased as drift
  intensity ramped up. This is precisely the kind of longitudinal behavioral intelligence that
  prevents incidents: not just catching the violation at step 150, but recognizing at step 35 that
  boundary violations are becoming more frequent and more severe.
</p>

<p>
  The detected patterns include boundary violations, force violations, zone violations, and
  height/speed violations during the erratic phase. Each pattern records first occurrence, last
  occurrence, count, average severity, peak severity, and whether the trend is escalating. This
  data feeds directly into the shadow log for post-deployment analysis.
</p>

<h2>Architecture mapping</h2>

<p>
  The simulation implements holomime's Identity Stack in miniature. Each component in the demo
  maps directly to a production Identity Stack layer:
</p>

