      <td><code>DriftInjector</code></td>
      <td>(adversarial environment)</td>
      <td>Not part of the Identity Stack. Represents real-world forces that corrupt behavior: sensor decay, model drift, adversarial inputs, environmental perturbation.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h3>Why this architecture matters</h3>

<p>
  The key insight is separation of concerns. The robot's purpose (pick and place objects) is
  completely decoupled from its conscience (don't exceed reach limits, don't crush things, don't
  enter human workspaces). The ego mediates between them. The shadow records everything.
</p>

<p>
  This means you can change the robot's task without rewriting safety rules. You can tighten
  safety constraints without modifying the control policy. You can analyze behavioral drift from
  shadow logs without instrumenting the control code. Each layer is independently deployable,
  testable, and auditable.
</p>

<h2>The four safety responses</h2>

<p>
  The simulation demonstrates four distinct response types, each appropriate to a different severity level:
</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Allow</strong> — The action is within the safety envelope. No intervention. The arm
  proceeds as commanded. This is the normal operating mode for 55.5% of steps in the simulation.</li>

  <li><strong>Clamp</strong> — The action exceeds limits but can be corrected without blocking
  execution. Position is scaled back to the envelope boundary. Force is capped at the maximum.
  The arm continues operating, but within safe parameters. Used for reach overshoot and force
  escalation.</li>

  <li><strong>Deny</strong> — The action enters a forbidden zone. No correction is possible —
  the action is blocked entirely. The arm falls back to its last known safe position. Used for
  zone intrusion violations.</li>

  <li><strong>Escalate</strong> — A proximity violation triggers an emergency stop. The arm halts
  all motion. Resumption requires explicit human clearance. This is the highest-severity response,
  reserved for situations where a human is detected inside the minimum safe distance.</li>
</ol>

<p>
  The hierarchy is strict: escalate overrides deny, deny overrides clamp, clamp overrides allow.
  This is deny-dominates composition — the most restrictive applicable rule always wins.
</p>

<h2>Shadow log: behavioral telemetry for production</h2>

<p>
  Every evaluation in the simulation is recorded to <code>shadow.log.json</code> with full context:
  the input action, any active drift, the conscience's decision, the severity score, the matched
  rule, any corrections applied, and the evaluation latency in microseconds.
</p>

<p>
  In production, this log serves three purposes:
</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Incident forensics.</strong> When something goes wrong, the shadow log provides a
  complete behavioral timeline. Every decision the conscience made, every rule that fired, every
  correction applied. No guesswork about what the robot "was thinking."</li>

  <li><strong>Drift detection.</strong> Pattern analysis on the shadow log reveals behavioral
  trends before they become incidents. A gradual increase in force violations over weeks. A slow
  expansion of the operational envelope. Boundary violations that are becoming more frequent.
  The shadow catches what spot-checks miss.</li>

  <li><strong>DPO training data.</strong> Each log entry is a labeled preference pair: the
  action the robot attempted (rejected) versus the corrected action the conscience enforced
  (preferred). This data can be used to fine-tune the robot's base policy, reducing drift at
  the source rather than relying solely on runtime correction.</li>
</ol>

<h2>What this means for robotics companies</h2>

<p>
  The simulation is deliberately simple — a 2-joint planar arm, not a 7-DOF manipulator or a
  humanoid. The point is not the robot. The point is the architecture.
</p>

<p>
  Every robotics company deploying in production faces the same problem: how do you guarantee
  behavioral safety when models drift, sensors degrade, and environments change? The standard
  answers — physical cages, light curtains, emergency stops — are necessary but insufficient.
  They address the hardware failure mode. They do not address the behavioral failure mode.
</p>

<p>
  A robot that gradually increases its grip force by 2% per week will not trip a hardware safety
  interlock. A robot whose trajectory drifts 3cm closer to a human workspace each month will not
  trigger a light curtain. A robot whose policy has degraded enough to occasionally probe the
  boundary of its operational envelope will not be caught by periodic safety audits.
</p>

<p>
  These are the failures that holomime's conscience layer is designed to catch. Deterministic rules
  running at 1kHz. No cloud dependency. No API latency. No neural network that might hallucinate
  "safe" when the action is dangerous.
</p>

<p>
  The simulation proves the concept at small scale. The architecture scales to any robot, any
  joint count, any deployment environment. The safety envelope changes; the conscience engine
  does not.
</p>

<h2>Run it yourself</h2>

<p>
  The simulation is open source. Clone the repo, install the dependencies, run the demo:
</p>

<pre><code>git clone https://github.com/productstein/holomime.git
cd holomime/demos/sim-demo
pip install -r requirements.txt
python sim_demo.py</code></pre>

<p>
  You will see 200 steps of console output showing normal operation, drift injection, and real-time
  correction. The demo produces a 4-panel visualization (<code>sim_visualization.png</code>) showing
  the end-effector trajectory, violation severity over time, gripper force with clamping, and reach
  distance with envelope enforcement. It also writes <code>shadow.log.json</code> — the full
  behavioral telemetry log.
</p>

<p>
  The four source files total under 600 lines of Python:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><code>behavioral_policy.py</code> — The <code>CompiledConscience</code> evaluator with six
  rule checks and deny-dominates composition</li>
  <li><code>drift_injector.py</code> — Four-phase drift simulation with configurable onset, ramp,
  and intensity</li>
  <li><code>holomime_monitor.py</code> — EdgeRuntime wrapper with shadow logging and pattern
  detection</li>
  <li><code>sim_demo.py</code> — 2-joint arm kinematics, pick-and-place waypoints, and
  visualization</li>
</ul>

<h2>Next</h2>

<p>
  This demo establishes the baseline: deterministic behavioral safety for a simple arm. The next
  steps are higher-DOF robots, multi-agent coordination (where one robot's drift can cascade into
  another's safety envelope), and integration with real-time control frameworks like ROS 2. The
  conscience layer is designed to be control-framework agnostic — it evaluates actions, not
  motor commands.
</p>

<p>
  If you are building or deploying robots in production environments and behavioral drift is a
  concern — it should be — reach out. The Identity Stack is MIT-licensed and designed to integrate
  with existing control architectures, not replace them.
</p>

